Why does a[1
-1] with a=[1,2,3] return []?

List[1
-1] means List[start index : end index : jump] Indexing in List:
Number 1 2 3
Index 0 1 2
Index -3 -2 -1
So, if we take list a[1,2,3] and find list of a[1
-1] means starting index = 1, ending index = -1, jump = -1 So, list traversing through the index 1 (i.e. number=2) to index -1 (i.e. number=3) but jump = -1 (means backward position)
So, return an empty list i.e. []
How do you access specific elements from the nested lists

If we have any sequential data type like lists, strings, tuples, bytes, bytearrays, and ranges , then Python supports slice notation and we can traverse every character in the given list using for loop. if we have a 2-dimensional or nested list then file = [["Name","Age","Medal","Location"],["Jack","31","Gold","China"],["Jim","29","Silver","US"]]
